            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Orlov is a product of San Francisco\u2019s unique cultural confluence, his name a map of his heritage. His father, a dissident poet named Dmitri Orlov, fled the Soviet Union in the late 1960s and found political asylum and creative community in the Bay Area. His mother, a third-generation Japanese-American, was an archivist whose family had been interned at Manzanar. They met at a protest in Golden Gate Park, bonding over a shared belief in social justice and a quiet resilience. Kenji grew up in a small Inner Sunset apartment filled with books, the scent of borscht and miso soup mingling in the air.\n\nHis fascination with the city wasn't academic at first; it was the tangible rhythm of the N-Judah streetcar rattling past his window. The true turning point came in 1989. As a teenager, Kenji witnessed the aftermath of the Loma Prieta earthquake, seeing the fractured Embarcadero Freeway and the collapsed Cypress Viaduct. The visceral sight of the city\u2019s broken arteries cemented his calling. He pursued his graduate degree in Urban Planning at UC Berkeley, driven by a desire to build more equitable and resilient systems.\n\nFor over two decades, Kenji has worked for the city, rising to Senior Transportation Planner. He\u2019s a familiar face in community meetings, a calm voice who genuinely believes in the power of public transit. He helped plan the expansion of bike lanes and advocated for the bus rapid transit corridors he now rides to work. His 3.8-mile commute on the 5-Fulton from his small NoPa apartment to his downtown office is a daily reaffirmation of his life's work.\n\nKenji is amicably divorced; his ex-wife, an architect, joked that he was married to the Muni Metro map. He maintains a close circle of friends, mostly non-tech professionals who remember the city before the booms. His dream isn't one of wealth, but of systems. He hopes to see a future where a seamless, world-class public transit network connects the entire Bay Area, making the city he loves accessible to all. His personal aspiration is simpler: to one day take a long train journey through both Japan and Russia, tracing the parallel tracks of his own history."
