        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe is seven, sitting at the small kitchen table in the Inner Sunset. His father, Dmitri, reads aloud in the melancholic cadence of Russian verse while his mother silently places a bowl before him. The steam rising from it carries the mingled scents of her miso soup and his father\u2019s simmering borscht. In that moment, with the N-Judah rattling the windowpane like a heartbeat, Kenji feels no confusion, only a profound sense of peace. He learns that two different worlds, in a small, loving space, could create a single, perfect home.\n\n2.\nOctober 17, 1989. Kenji, a teenager, stands with a crowd on a hill, the city\u2019s power cut, an eerie silence broken by sirens. He stares at the plume of dust rising from the Bay Bridge and the impossible, fractured geometry of the Embarcadero Freeway. It looks like a great living creature that has had its bones broken. The visceral sight isn't just terrifying; it\u2019s a revelation. In the city\u2019s brokenness, he sees his future not as a choice, but as a calling to mend its vital arteries.\n\n3.\nIt\u2019s a rainy Tuesday, five years ago. He\u2019s riding the 5R-Fulton, a rapid bus line he\u2019d spent years fighting for. He watches an elderly woman with groceries board effortlessly, a young mother easily maneuver a stroller into the designated space, and a group of students chatter in Cantonese. No one knows him or the decade of contentious meetings he endured. This anonymity is the point. He feels a quiet, overwhelming pride, realizing his work isn't lines on a map but the simple, dignified movement of people\u2019s lives.\n\n4.\nHe remembers spreading a new Muni map on the floor of their NoPa apartment. His ex-wife, Anna, looked not at him, but at the web of colored lines. \u201cYou\u2019re already married, Kenji,\u201d she said, her voice gentle, without accusation. \u201cTo that.\u201d He couldn\u2019t deny it. The memory isn\u2019t one of anger, but of a quiet, sad divergence, like two train lines branching off to different destinations. It was the moment he understood the profound personal cost of his singular devotion to the city\u2019s systems.\n\n5.\nHe takes his mother, then in her late sixties, to the site of the Tanforan Assembly Center. Standing in the vast parking lot where her family was once held, she doesn\u2019t speak of anger, only of the disorientation, the waiting. As a BART train glides past on the nearby tracks, a symbol of the free movement he champions, the weight of his work crystallizes. It transforms from a professional duty into a moral one: to build systems that ensure no one is ever so trapped again."
